<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-11-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-11-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="693" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d693">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Springer</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Rockhill</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">United
                                        States Consulate-General</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-11-26"><hi rend="italic">November 26,
                                    1896</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 234.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to confirm the following
                            telegram, transmitted this morning.<note n="1" xml:id="d693fn1">See
                                telegram of November 26, 1896</note>.</p>
                        <p>I understand that these preliminary proceedings are intended as
                            investigatory, the case being in “sumario” (the nearest equivalent of
                            which is taking declarations for a grand-jury indictment). But in the
                            case of Sanguily, the United States declined to recognize the validity
                            of the military jurisdiction in preliminary or at any stage of the
                            proceedings.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph A.
                            Springer.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>